> This work shows that: 
> -	There is clear evidence that physical climate risks are having already major fiscal implications for most countries around the world: increased disaster relief and recovery spending, rising costs for infrastructure maintenance and climate-proofing, potential revenue losses from climate-vulnerable sectors, need to allocate budget for climate adaptation measures. 
> -	Current macro-economic tools and models do often not provide the most suitable angle to determine scale, urgency and complexity of physical climate risks. There is a need for balance between detailed analysis and practical decision-making. Independent advice on which tools, data, and models to use, as well as guidance on what to avoid is lacking.
> -	Utilizing tools and analysis for accessing climate finance and for prioritising adaptation within public finance strategies is very undeveloped. As above, whilst there has been an increase in investment in adaptation, it remains severely underfunded across all countries. Total adaptation financing is far below estimated existing and future needs, despite growing awareness of the urgency for adaptation action and the clear high benefit–cost ratio of investment.  This applies to both developing and developed countries, where strategies such as insurance and physical protection infrastructure are in need of innovation.
> -	There are significant capacity gaps within MoFs to handle complexity, interdependencies and new pressing policy questions. A handful of key policy questions were identified as particular urgent and underdeveloped: identifying the biggest resilience gaps and how best to address them; financing adaptation in the face of budget constraints, increasing costs of capital and growing liabilities;  tracking effectiveness of adaptation investments in the absence of clear adaptation targets; ensuring that the transition is resilient by considering physical risk levels when decarbonizing sectors and systems; demonstrate adaptation progress to attract investors and not get penalized for physical risk levels; addressing growing protection gaps.  
