> Certainly! Here's a concise, two-page background document explaining the project, its objectives, and the rationale for conducting interviews:
> 
> ---
> 
> ### Project Background and Objectives
> 
> **Project Title:** Accelerating Investment in Adaptation and Resilience by Economic Decision-Makers
> 
> **Partners:** Grantham Institute on Climate Change and Environment (LSE), Marsh McLennan, Paul Watkiss Associates, and University of Delaware
> 
> **Funded by:** The Gates Foundation
> 
> #### Introduction & Context
> 
> As climate change continues to intensify, it imposes severe fiscal pressures on economies worldwide. The urgency for adaptation investment grows, yet it remains critically underfunded. Finance Ministers and key economic decision-makers are crucial in bridging this gap, but require compelling, evidence-based arguments to prioritize adaptation alongside mitigation efforts.
> 
> The project aims to address this need by creating a compelling body of work that highlights the macroeconomic costs of inaction and the substantial benefits of strategic investment in climate adaptation. This work will support informed discussions and policymaking leading up to COP30 in Belém, Brazil.
> 
> #### Objectives
> 
> 1. **Review & Synthesis:** Conduct a comprehensive global review of existing literature to assess the economic costs of inaction versus the benefits of adaptation investments.
> 2. **Case Studies Development:** Analyze the adaptation outcomes in countries like the UK, Rwanda, Kenya, Nigeria, Brazil, and Bangladesh, focusing on success factors, financing mechanisms, and national-scale benefits.
> 3. **Promote Evidence-Based Policy:** Provide Finance Ministries with actionable insights and tailored frameworks for integrating adaptation into fiscal planning and economic strategies.
> 4. **Inform Decision-Makers:** Develop strategies to communicate the fiscal and economic advantages of adaptation, including its role in unlocking international funding and supporting national development objectives.
> 
> #### Why We Want to Conduct Interviews
> 
> To achieve the objectives above, it is critical to understand the real-world needs and constraints of Finance Ministries and economic decision-makers. Interviews with these stakeholders will provide:
> 
> - **Contextual Insights:** Direct feedback on the relevance and applicability of existing macroeconomic models and cost assessments, ensuring the synthesis aligns with the knowledge gaps and decision-making processes in Finance Ministries.
> 
> - **Experience Sharing:** Valuable case study data from countries that exemplify successful adaptation strategies or face challenges in implementation, thereby providing nuanced, context-specific narratives.
> 
> - **Actionable Recommendations:** Perspectives on which types of investments are most compelling, under what circumstances, and how international funding and policy dynamics can be optimized to support adaptation efforts.
> 
> - **Validation & Feedback:** A platform to test preliminary findings, gather expert validation, and refine communications to better resonate with economic policymakers and influencers.
> 
> #### Methodology & Approach
> 
> The project will employ a mix of literature reviews, country-specific data synthesis, and interviews to:
> 
> - **Analyze Macroeconomic Impact:** Utilize a blend of macroeconomic models, empirical studies, and AI-aided literature review to assess the economic implications of adaptation.
> - **Develop Case Studies:** Focus on real-world examples to illustrate economic outcomes of adaptation investments, tailor messages to resonate with national economic priorities, and explore sustainable financing options.
> - **Iterative Feedback:** Engage stakeholders continuously throughout the project to ensure the findings are relevant, credible, and poised to drive policy action.
> 
> ---
> 
> This two-pager aims to clearly articulate the project's scope and emphasize the importance of stakeholder engagement in refining the outcomes and enhancing the impact of the findings.
